  1. What is the EPSG code of the Counties dataset? Is this a geographic or a projected coordinate reference system? (Om other words, does this CRS use angular or planar coordinate units?) To what datum is this CRS associated? (Tip: look for the EPSG code on https://epsg.io)

ANSWER: ID[EPSG,4269]. This dataset uses a geographic coordinate reference system (gcs), and its CRS uses a angular coordinate units. The datum is the datum is North America Datum of 1983.

Map the pattern of gage height data

Now we can examine where the flooding appears most acute by visualizing gage heights spatially. 19. Plot the gage sites on top of counties (using mapview, ggplot, or leaflet) * Show the magnitude of gage height by color, shape, other visualization technique.

#Map the points, sized by gage height
ggplot() +
  # Plot Nebraska counties in a light blue color
  geom_sf(data = counties_sf, fill = "lightgrey", color = "black") +
  
  # Plot gage locations as red points
  geom_sf(data = gage_sf_joined, 
          aes(color = "red", size = gage_ht)) +
  # Add titles
  ggtitle("NWIS Gage Pattern Height in Nebraska Counties")

SPATIAL ANALYSIS

Up next we will do some spatial analysis with our data. To prepare for this, we should transform our data into a projected coordinate system. Well choose UTM Zone 14N (EPGS = 32614).

Transform the counties and gage site datasets to UTM Zone 14N

  1. Transform the counties and gage sf datasets to UTM Zone 14N (EPGS = 32614).
  2. Using mapview or ggplot, plot the data so that each can be seen as different colors
#20 Transform the counties and gage location datasets to UTM Zone 14
gage_sf_transformed <- st_transform(gage_sf_joined, crs = 32614)
counties_sf_transformed <- st_transform(counties_sf, crs= 32614) 

#21 Plot the data
mapview(counties_sf, col.regions = "lightpink", alpha.regions = 0.3, 
        layer.name = "Counties") +
  mapview(gage_sf_transformed, zcol = "gage_ht", legend = TRUE, 
          layer.name = "Gage Height")

Select the gages falling within a given county

Now lets zoom into a particular county and examine the gages located there. 22. Select Lancaster county from your projected county sf dataframe 23. Select the gage sites falling within that county to a new spatial dataframe 24. Select the gage sites within 15km of the county to a new spatial dataframe 25. Create a plot showing (each symbolized distinctly): * all Nebraska counties, * the selected county, * the gage sites in that county, * and the gage sites within 15 km of the county

#22 Select the county (Lancaster)
selected_county <- counties_sf_transformed %>% 
  filter(NAME %in% c("Lancaster")) 

#23 Spatially select gages within the selected county
gages_within_county <- gage_sf_transformed %>%
  st_intersection(selected_county)
## Warning: attribute variables are assumed to be spatially constant throughout
## all geometries
#24 Spatially select gages within 15 k of the selected county
# buffer for the selected county first
county_buffer <- st_buffer(selected_county, 15000) 
gages_within_15km <- gage_sf_transformed %>%
  st_intersection(county_buffer)
## Warning: attribute variables are assumed to be spatially constant throughout
## all geometries
#25 Plot
ggplot() +
  # Plot counties as a base layer, fill with NA to only outline
  geom_sf(data = counties_sf, aes(color = "All Counties in Nebraska"), 
          size = 0.5) +
  geom_sf(data = selected_county, aes(fill = "Selected County"), 
          color = "black", size = 0.5) +
  geom_sf(data = gages_within_15km, aes(color = "Gages within 15 km"), 
          size = 1) +
  geom_sf(data = gages_within_county, aes(color = "Gages within County"), 
          size = 1) +
  
  # Customize color and fill scales for legends
  scale_color_manual(
    values = c("All Counties in Nebraska" = "black", 
               "Gages within 15 km" = "blue", 
               "Gages within County" = "red"),
    name = "Layer"
  ) +
  scale_fill_manual(
    values = c("Selected County" = "lightgreen"),
  ) +
  
  # Add title and theme adjustments
  ggtitle("Gages in Lancaster County, Nebraska and within Area of 15km") +
  theme_minimal()+
  theme(legend.position = "right")
